   <definition xml:id="def-hyperbola">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>hyperbola</term> is the set of all points such that the difference of the distances from the point <m>(x,y)</m> to a pair of distinct points (called foci) is a fixed constant.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="base-hyperbola">
        <caption>A plot of an hyperbola with foci in green</caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-base-hyperbola" platform="sage" width="125%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            var('t')
            tval=0.5
            a=2
            c=3
            d=1
            b=sqrt(c^2-a^2)
            xo=3
            os=0.25
            @interact
            def hyperbolabase(tval=slider(-1.25,1.25,default=0.6,display_value=False)):
                plot3=point((c,0),color="green",size=20,axes=True,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],ticks=[[],[]])
                plot3+=point((-c,0),color="green",size=20)
                plot3+=line([(c,0),(a*sec(tval),b*tan(tval))],color="red")
                plot3+=line([(-c,0),(a*sec(tval),b*tan(tval))],color="blue")
                plot3+=point((a*sec(tval),b*tan(tval)),color="purple",size=20)
                rv=sqrt((a*sec(tval)-c)^2+(b*tan(tval))^2)
                bv=sqrt((a*sec(tval)+c)^2+(b*tan(tval))^2)
                plot3+=parametric_plot((a*sec(t),b*tan(t)),(t,-1.25,1.25),color="black")
                plot3+=parametric_plot((-a*sec(t),b*tan(t)),(t,-1.25,1.25),color="black")
                plot3+=line([(xo+bv,d),(xo-rv+bv,d)],color="red")+line([(xo,d-os/2),(xo+bv,d-os/2)],color="blue")
                plot3+=line([(xo,d+os),(xo+2*a,d+os)],color="green")
                plot3+=line([(-3*a,-3*b),(3*a,3*b)],color="gray",linestyle="--")
                plot3+=line([(-3*a,3*b),(3*a,-3*b)],color="gray",linestyle="--")
                show(plot3,aspect_ratio=1,xmin=-5,xmax=11,ymin=-5,ymax=5)
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        In the interact above, you can see how as you move around the hyperbola, the difference of the lengths of the blue and red segments remains constant (shown in green). Additionally, you can see that a hyperbola has asymptotic behavior in that as you approach the edges of the plot, the hyperbola will get very close to the asymptote lines (shown with a dashed line). 
      </p>
    </statement>
   </definition>
