   <definition xml:id="def-parabola">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>parabola</term> is the set of all points that are the same distance from a point (called the focus) and a line (called the directrix).
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="base-parabola">
        <caption>A plot of an parabola with the focus in green and the directrix shown as a dashed line</caption>
        <interactive title="interactive-base-parabola" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
          <slate surface="sage">
            @interact
            def parabolabase(tval=slider(-4,4,0.1,default=1.6,display_value=False,label="Move Point on Parabola")):
              var('t')
              c=1
              plot4=point((c,0),color="green",size=20,axes=True,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],ticks=[[],[]])
              plot4+=line([(tval^2/4,tval),(-c,tval)],color="red")
              plot4+=line([(tval^2/4,tval),(c,0)],color="blue")
              plot4+=point((tval^2/4,tval),color="purple",size=20)
              plot4+=parametric_plot((t^2/4,t),(t,-4,4),color="black")
              plot4+=line([(-1,-8),(-1,8)],color="gray",linestyle="--")
              plot4+=line([(-c,3.9),(tval^2/4,3.9)],color="red")
              plot4+=line([(-c,3.8),(tval^2/4,3.8)],color="blue")
              show(plot4,aspect_ratio=1,xmin=-4,xmax=4,ymin=-4,ymax=4)
          </slate>
        </interactive>
      </figure>
      <p>
        In the interact above, you can see how as you move around the parabola, the lengths of the blue and red segments remains the same as each other. The point that is half way between the focus and the directrix is referred to as the center and the vertex of the parabola.
      </p>
    </statement>
   </definition>
